rest_of_day_open: I have many tasks to complete this week before the start of classes next week at my university. My supervisor has placed numerous obstacles in my path, so the work is difficult and challenging. I know that I have a good base of support, so I'm working my way around the obstacles.
critical_positive: I appreciated that both of us sought out commonalities immediately. There was a sense that we both wanted the other person to do well at the task, which makes sense because we're both teachers and love to see other people succeed. Daniqua (I'm sure I misspelled her delightful name) added stories and humor to the conversation that kept our interaction light and fun, but she wasn't afraid to delve into more sensitive topics.
critical_negative: The conversation was a bit awkward at first as we were trying to find common ground, so the responses were slower and less enthusiastic at the very beginning. There was a sense that we were both trying to make the best of the situation instead of truly connecting with each other.

rest_of_day_open: I feel it will be somewhat relaxed, even with the amount of classwork I have to deal with. I will have time to do things I like for myself but also get my work done. I don't have to go to the gym this week, so I'll have the mornings for myself fully, which will be fun, especially for the weekend.
critical_positive: What worked the best was that we were both educators who both took a longer road to get to teach. The fact that she understood how this world was for us felt great and it allowed me to become comfortable with her. She was lovely to have these discussions with because I don't have a lot of teacher friends.
critical_negative: I feel that not much worked against us. If I want to become critical, I feel at times I spoke over her when I didn't really mean to. I think I was just excited to share a thought but I attempted to reign it in so she could speak freely without me jumping on her thoughts.
